    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but it sounds pretty intense. It's a bit scary how broad \"any and all losses\" is. Are there any specific types of \"hidden\" or sneaky things in a clause like this that I should be looking out for? Like, is there stuff in there that might not be obvious on first read?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Any and all losses\" is indeed a wide net, and you're right to be wary; it's the kind of language that can trap you in a situation with the same subtle traps as a poorly constructed snare. You need to look for the *scope* of the trigger events, not just the resulting damages. A sneaky thing to watch for is whether the clause attempts to cover things that are *outside* your control, like the Disclosing Party's own negligence.\n\nIf the clause doesn't explicitly carve out the Disclosing Party's own fault, you could end up having to pay for their mistakes, which is a classic \"gotcha.\" It's often hidden in the fine print, buried under layers of legalese, making it look like it applies to everything, even if it shouldn't. It's a perfect example of how a seemingly simple agreement can become a massive, unpredictable liability pile-up.",
      "source": "target",
