    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "These clauses don't always *intend* to be sneaky, but they are certainly designed to be comprehensive, which often makes them feel like a trap, much like a poorly disguised patch of mud that trips you up when you're running toward a good patch of dry ground. The way they \"hide\" risk is by using expansive, all-encompassing language—words like \"any,\" \"all,\" \"arising out of,\" and \"in connection with.\"\n\nThese broad phrases are like a massive, poorly defined territory that the Disclosing Party claims. Instead of listing specific scenarios (e.g., \"if you leak the customer list\"), they use these giant nets of language that catch everything, even the things you didn't anticipate. It's the difference between saying, \"If you steal the gold,\" and saying, \"If a single dust mote from your workshop lands on the gold, we hold you responsible for the entire mountain.\"\n\nThe risk is hidden in the *lack* of specificity. If the contract had listed every single way you could fail, it would be long, but it would be clear. Because it uses these sweeping terms, it allows the Disclosing Party to argue that *any* connection—even",
